把这几段的逻辑和我说下：\subsection{Unified Multimodal Models}
Unified multimodal models (UMMs) aim to handle multiple vision-language tasks---such as understanding, generation, and editing---within a single model family and training pipeline, rather than relying on specialized models for each capability. Compared with conventional VLMs that primarily focus on perception and text generation, UMMs are designed to support a broader set of modalities (image, text, and even video), diverse input-output formats (e.g., text-to-image, image-to-text, image-to-image), and unified instruction following. A typical route is to couple a strong language backbone with a visual tokenizer/latent representation, enabling the model to both ``read'' and ``write'' visual content in a unified token space. This direction is motivated by practical deployment needs (a single general-purpose agent) and by the observation that generation and understanding can mutually reinforce through joint training.
\paragraph{Modeling paradigms.}
Existing UMMs can be roughly categorized by their generative representations. \emph{Discrete-token} approaches encode images into discrete visual tokens and use an autoregressive transformer to generate both text and image tokens, naturally unifying multimodal I/O and simplifying instruction conditioning. \emph{Latent diffusion / flow} based approaches instead attach a diffusion-style image generator or editor to a language controller, where the LLM plans or conditions the generation process while the visual module synthesizes high-fidelity pixels. Hybrid designs are also common, combining discrete representations for alignment and reasoning with diffusion for photorealistic rendering. Regardless of the paradigm, key challenges include: balancing heterogeneous objectives, preventing catastrophic interference between tasks, and achieving strong prompt faithfulness and text rendering accuracy under a unified training recipe.
\paragraph{Representative unified models.}
Recent work has proposed multiple unified systems spanning both academic and industrial settings, including Bagel~\cite{deng2025bagel}, OneCAT~\cite{li2025onecat}, Janus-Pro~\cite{chen2025janus}, Show-o2~\cite{xie2025show}, Ovis-U1~\cite{wang2025ovis}, Lumina-DiMOO~\cite{xin2025lumina}, and Uniworld-V1/V2~\cite{li2025uniworld} , which attempt to consolidate multimodal understanding and generation within one architecture or a closely coupled model suite. In addition,  Emu3.5~\cite{cui2025emu3} explore broader ``world mdoel'' modeling, while Mogao~\cite{liao2025mogao} and Ming-UniVision~\cite{huang2025ming} target strong general-purpose multimodal capabilities under unified training. BLIP-3o~\cite{chen2025blip3} and BLIP3o-NEXT~\cite{chen2025blip3o} further extend the BLIP family toward more general multimodal agents, and Lavida-O~\cite{li2025lavida} provides another representative effort for unifying vision-language tasks with instruction tuning.
\paragraph{Unified training and scaling trends.}
A growing body of work explores unified data and objective design to improve generalization across tasks, such as UniGen-1.5~\cite{tian2025unigen}, UniLiP~\cite{tang2025unilip}, OpenUni~\cite{wu2025openuni}, and Skywork UniPic~\cite{wang2025skywork}. These models typically emphasize large-scale interleaved multimodal data, multi-task instruction tuning, and careful sampling/weighting strategies to stabilize training. Meanwhile, system-level designs such as MANZANO~\cite{modelmanzano}, EMMA~\cite{he2025emmaefficientmultimodalunderstanding}, MammothModa2~\cite{shen2025mammothmoda2}, and Tuna~\cite{liu2025tuna} investigate scalable infrastructure, data pipelines, and training recipes that enable unified models to grow in size and capability. Overall, the literature indicates a clear trend toward building single, instruction-following multimodal foundation models that can seamlessly switch among understanding, generation, and editing, while maintaining high visual fidelity and robust semantic alignment.
